<br>
His post said this when explaining the skill <br>
<br>
&quot;When a spell is cast a roll is thrown to see if it receives the specialisation bonus.  The higher your specialization skill the more likely it is the roll will succeed, and the greater the benefit of the roll.  A successful roll will do two things: <br>
<br>
It will reduce the mana used on the spell. <br>
It will reduce the chance of fizzling.<br>
 <br>
An unsuccessful roll will merely cause you to cast the spell with normal mana cost and fizzle chance.&quot;<br>
<br>
This has been posted on many websites and is where i recieved my thoughts on the subject.<br>
<br>
Also if you look at the description of SCM it as well sounds as if there is a specilization &quot;check&quot; when a spell is cast.<br>
<br>
&quot;This ability gives you an increased chance of making your specilization checks. It reduces your chance to fizzle and increases the chance to lower the mana cost for the spell by 5, 15, and 30 percent.&quot;<br>
<br>
I think what you were listing is what mana savings most people averaged when testing SCM, but that wouldn't mean that is what you get every time.<br>
<br>
I personally would like it if the skill was the way you described, as it sounds to me that would be a more consistant mana savings...but i just dont see any other information that confirms it. Please let me know if you do tho, i would love to learn the correct info if i was wrong in my way of thinking. <br>
